How is E.Coli negatively affecting us?

E.Coli can negatively affect those with a weak immune system. These people tend to be younger or older people. E.Coli is more severe as there digestive system isn't strong.

People in low income communities are also affected do to a lack of accessibility. They don't have money to get the medication for the treatment such as Bactrim, septra, Monurol, Macrobid, Maccrodantin 

Many people believe that E.Coli is mainly in meats. However, it is found in a multifarious amount of fruits and vegetables. This is because there is a lack of washing these foods properly. 

E.Coli

Ground beef is especially risky, because the bacteria can spread when meat is ground up. Symptoms include severe abdominal cramps, watery diarrhea, and vomiting. The illness typically develops several days after exposure and can be severe in vulnerable people

How E.Coli affects Poverty vs. Rich

Solutions and ways to prevent E.Coli

Intriguing facts 

Keep raw foods separate. This includes using separate cutting boards for raw meat and foods, such as vegetables and fruits. Never put cooked hamburgers on the same plate you used for raw patties. Wash your hands. Wash your hands after preparing or eating food, using the toilet, or changing diapers. Make sure that children also wash their hands before eating, after using the bathroom and after contact with animals.

No vaccine or medication can protect you from E. coli-based illness, though researchers are investigating potential vaccines.


E. coli was first discovered in 1885 by Theodor Escherich, a German bacteriologist


Once a person has become infected with E. coli it can take anywhere from one day to ten days for symptoms to appear.



In the United States there are approximately 265,000 cases of E. coli STEC infection each year.
